Background and Research Question

The main question that I have from this dataset is what kind of movement of animal and dive should we consider as foraging behaviour and at what time of the day those foraging behaviour appear? There is clear water at Guadalupe Island (GI) and it is believed that the hunting happens in deeper water where the light level is low (Papastamatiou et al., 2021). From this information an interesting question arises: - Can we observe some periodic foraging behaviour at certain hours of the day? By analysing this data, we can make an inference if there is a specific hunting time for this shark or is it random.

From the accelerometer data, pitch and roll can be calculated. Pitch and roll represents the changes in body orientation.

Rotation around the front-to-back axis is called roll. Rotation around the side-to-side axis is called pitch. Rotation around the vertical axis is called yaw. I determined that there is a steady swimming between 1.35 and 1.41 hours and the stroking rate was determined as 0.30.

A good starting choice for the filter cut-off frequency is 70 percent of the stroking rate.

Complimentary filterning of a signal breaks two or more frequencies such that the sum of signals equal to original signal. In our case comp_filt function breaks down the accelerometer and magnatometer values into high frequencies and low frequency values.

fc <- 0.30*0.7
Af <- comp_filt(A,fc=fc)
Mf <- comp_filt(M,fc=fc)

Here, Ahigh is the high pass filtered acceleration and Alow is low pass filtered acceleration.

Alow <- Af[[1]]
Ahigh <- Af[[2]]
Mlow <- Mf[[1]]
Mhigh <- Mf[[2]]

The following lines from Mark Johnson Tagtools Practical 2 explains why Dynamic acceleration and Jerk are better metric to measure the prey capture.

Sudden changes in acceleration are often associated with prey capture attempts although they can also arise in other activities such as social encounters, grooming, and in attacks by predators. Rapid changes mean high frequencies and so these will show up in the high pass filtered acceleration, Ahigh, that you made with the complementary filter. Because we dont know what kind of movement is involved in a prey capture attempt, we dont know which axis of acceleration will be most relevant. It is easier in this case, to just compute the magnitude of the three axes - that way a peak in any or all axes will show up. This gives what is sometimes called the dynamic acceleration. Another way to emphasize rapid changes in acceleration is by differentiating acceleration to produce the jerk. This is effectively high-pass filtering acceleration with a filter that has a roughly constant slope - the higher the frequency, the more it is emphasised. - Mark Johnson Practical 2

Dynamic Acceleration

Overall, Body Dynamic acceleration is a proxy of activity and energy expenditure (Lopez et al., 2021). From Papastamatiou et al.(2021) it was found that ODBA values were highest during the afternoon hours (16:00) and when near the surface. However, they decreased significantly when the depth was increased and early morning time. While calculating OBDA, the static acceleration (which comes from the earths gravitational pull) is removed and only the dynamic acceleration is used which is the measure of true movement of the animal.

Jerk

Also, another important variable to understand is Jerk which is a proxy of fast movement of head and jaw. I am exploring the dataset to observe if there are high frequency acceleration signatures which indicates the feeding activity of shark.

Dead-reckoning ( Reconstruction of the track for White shark)

For the shark data, I assume that its body is aligned with the direction of its motion. Therefore, I used ptrack function for the path reconstruction. The ptrack is referred as pseudo-track based on speed and body pointing angle. The track is defined as meters of northward and eastward movement (termed northing and easting) relative to the animals position at the start of the measurements (which is defined as [0,0]).

The track3D function uses pitch, heading and depth data (if a starting point is provided) to reconstruct a track by fitting a state space model using a Kalman filter.

trackts2=track3D(z=P$data,phi=p$p,psi=h$h,sf=MN$AccX$sampling_rate,r=0.001,q1p=0.02,q2p=0.08,q3p=1.6e-05,tagonx=1000,tagony=1000,x=NA,y=NA)

#how many obs
nobs=length(trackts2$fit.rx)
plot(trackts2$fit.rx,trackts2$fit.ry,xlab="X",ylab="Y",pch=".",col=ifelse(P$data<150,3,2))
points(trackts2$fit.rx[c(1,nobs)],trackts2$fit.ry[c(1,nobs)],pch=21,bg=5:6)
legend("bottomleft",cex=0.5,legend=c("Surface","Below 150 m","Start","End"),col=c(3,2,5,6),pt.bg=c(NA,NA,5,6),pch=c(NA,NA,21,21),lty=c(1,1,NA,NA))
polygon(x=c(120,140,140,120),y=c(400,400,450,450))
arrows(x0=130,y0=400,x1=190,y1=80,length=0.1)

one important thing that I learnt from Mark Johnsons practical 3 is that tagonX (Easting of starting position (in meters, so requires projected data)) and tagonY (Northing of starting position (in meters, so requires projected data)) is required while generating p-tracks.In the example they are generated from the GPS latitude and longitude values. However, I have used 1000 m for both as set in tagtools R example because I dont have GPS coordinates. According to the Mark Johnson tutorial (practical 3), there could be many inaccuracies with the dead-reckoned tracks. For the best results we need to make a qualitative and quantitative assessment of dead-reckoned track with the GPS track.

Question: Is the dead-reckoned track that was reconstructed without starting position is a good representation of actual animal movement?
